{"title_page": "Kalinik II", "text_new": "{{short description|18th-century Serbian Orthodox patriarch}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type = \n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Kalinik II\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title = [[Archbishop of Pe\u0107 and Serbian Patriarch]]\n| image =\n| imagesize = 200\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| church = [[Serbian Orthodox Church]]\n| archdiocese = \n| province = \n| metropolis = \n| diocese = \n| see = [[Patriarchal Monastery of Pe\u0107]]\n| enthroned = 1765\n| ended = 1766\n| predecessor = [[Vasilije I, Serbian Patriarch|Vasilije I]]\n| opposed = \n| successor = [[Dimitrije, Serbian Patriarch|Dimitrije I]]\n| ordination = \n| consecration = \n| rank = \n| other_post =\n| motto =\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| buried = \n| nationality = [[Rum Millet]] (Ottoman Empire)\n| religion = [[Eastern Orthodox Christianity]]\n| residence = \n| parents =\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| occupation = Primate of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]]\n| profession = \n| alma_mater = \n| signature = \n| other = \n}}\n\n'''Kalinik II''' ({{lang-sr|\u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043a II}}, {{lang-el|\u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03af\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u0384}}, {{lang-la|Callinicus II}}) was [[Archbishop of Pe\u0107 and Serbian Patriarch]] from 1765 to 1766. He was the last holder of that office before the [[Ottoman Empire]] abolished the [[Serbian Patriarchate of Pe\u0107]] in 1766.{{sfn|\u0412\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b|1996|p=273-274}} As an ethnic Greek, he was seen as a foreigner among Serbs, who favored the deposed patriarch [[Vasilije I, Serbian Patriarch|Vasilije I]]. Since his tenure was marked by various internal conflicts, Kalinik decided to resign his post, and even went a step further: he sent a pre-agreed petition to the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]] asking for the abolition of the Serbian Patriarchate of Pe\u0107, citing accumulated debts as the main reason for this motion, signed by him and 5 other bishops. On 11 September 1766, the Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople convinced the [[Sultan]] to abolish the Serbian Patriarchate of Pe\u0107 and place its dioceses under the jurisdiction of Constantinople. That decision affected only Serbian dioceses under Ottoman rule, since Serbian Autonomous [[Metropolitanate of Karlovci]] in [[Habsburg Monarchy]] remained out of reach of Constantinopolitan [[Phanariotes]].{{sfn|\u0106irkovi\u0107|2004|p=177}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=\u0106irkovi\u0107|first=Sima|authorlink=Sima \u0106irkovi\u0107|year=2004|title=The Serbs|location=Malden|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Wc-DWRzoeIC}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Foti\u0107|first=Aleksandar|chapter=Serbian Orthodox Church|title=Encyclopedia of the Ottoman Empire|year=2008|location=New York|publisher=Infobase Publishing|pages=519\u2013520|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QjzYdCxumFcC}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|editor-last=Ka\u0161i\u0107|editor-first=Du\u0161an|title=Serbian Orthodox Church: Its past and present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_ujjAAAAMAAJ|volume=1|year=1965|location=Belgrade|publisher=Serbian Orthodox Church}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Kiminas|first=Demetrius|title=The Ecumenical Patriarchate: A History of Its Metropolitanates with Annotated Hierarch Catalogs|year=2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QLWqXrW2X-8C|publisher=Wildside Press LLC}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Pavlovich|first=Paul|title=The History of the Serbian Orthodox Church|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1hzZAAAAMAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Serbian Heritage Books}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=\u0421\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0435\u043f\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b|first=\u0402\u043e\u043a\u043e \u041c.|authorlink=\u0110oko M. Slijep\u010devi\u0107|title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0435 \u0446\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0435 (History of the Serbian Orthodox Church)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M9faAAAAMAAJ|volume=\u043a\u045a. 1|year=1962|location=\u041c\u0438\u043d\u0445\u0435\u043d|publisher=\u0418\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0430}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=\u0412\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b|first=\u0421\u0430\u0432\u0430|year=1996|authorlink=Sava Vukovi\u0107 (bishop)|title=\u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0458\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0438 \u043e\u0434 \u0434\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0433 \u0434\u043e \u0434\u0432\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0433 \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430 (Serbian Hierarchs from the 9th to the 20th Century)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VBzkAAAAMAAJ|location=\u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434|publisher=\u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.spc.rs/eng/church Official site of the Serbian Orthodox Church: Serbian Archbishops and Patriarchs]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|eo}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Vasilije I, Serbian Patriarch|Vasilije I]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Serbian Patriarch]] | years = 1765\u20131766 }}\n{{s-vac|reason = Post abolished by Ottoman Empire|next= [[Dimitrije, Serbian Patriarch|Dimitrije]]|as=patriarch from 1920}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Serbian Orthodox leaders}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kalinik 02, Serbian Patriarch}}\n[[Category:Patriarchs of the Serbian Orthodox Church|Kalinik II]]\n[[Category:18th-century Eastern Orthodox bishops]]\n[[Category:Serbian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:18th-century Greek people]]\n\n{{serbia-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|18th-century Serbian Orthodox patriarch}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type = \n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Kalinik II\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title = [[Archbishop of Pe\u0107 and Serbian Patriarch]]\n| image =\n| i